Free Speech on College Campuses¶

Independent unsupervised learning project. The goals are

  1. to attempt to recover a latent variable representing political correctness,
  2. to see if students can be clustered by their positions on free speech, and
  3. to assess the relationship between such clusters or latent variables and students' political affiliations.

The notebook is organized in roughly the order the goals are listed. At the beginning and end of the notebook there is additional data exploration. I also include some Markdown that helps guide users along the CRISP-DM approach to organizing the data analysis process:

  1. Business Understanding
  2. Data Understanding
  3. Prepare Data
  4. Data Modeling
  5. Evaluate the Results

Business Understanding¶

College students once led the nation in the push for free speech rights. Now some political pundits--especially Conservative pundits--have expressed concern that college students are leading the fight against free speech. The claim is that students are fighting hate speech in the name of inclusiveness, and in doing so are reducing the window of acceptable expression. Everyone dislikes hate speech and everyone likes inclusiveness, so what's the big deal? Well, it matters how students define "hate speech".

Students have rioted at the presence of popular, provocative conservative figures who hold mainstream conservative views. The best example is Ben Shapiro, whose views are something like a socially liberal version of Reaganism. Shapiro is popular among young conservatives, but despised by young liberals. Some young liberals consider Shapiro a "hateful" person because their moral principles differ so starkly.

Gallup and the Knight Foundation recently co-sponsored a survey of college students on their beliefs about free speech. They made that data available to the public. You can learn more here: https://heterodoxacademy.org/gallup-knight-foundation-study/

I sought to see if I could recover a latent variable called "Political Correctness", defined as the preference for reduction in free speech rights in order to increase inclusivitity. The concept of Political Correctness is at the heart of Conservative pundits' concerns, to the extent that students favor "unreasonable" restrictions on first amendment rights.

I also sought to see if students could be clustered by their views on free speech. Are students cleanly divided on the issue? Or is the distribution variance just a bit larger than it used to be?

Finally, I explored the relationship between free speech beliefs and self-identified political ideology. The exploration helps us understand the extent to which differences in free speech beliefs are actually political, or the extent to which differences in those beliefs can be conflated with existing political divisions.

Data Undersstanding¶

The dataset consists of survey responses from 3,014 colleges students.

The 14 variables associated with questions used in the Stanton Free Speech Index, discussed later, are used to index students' free speech views. These variables are used for latent variable analysis and cluster analysis.

The data also includes several variables describing students' responses to demographic questions, such as socioeconomic status and age. These variables are included as covariates in regression models used to explore the relationships between free speech beliefs and political affiliations.

The data includes variables describing students' responses to questions bout their political ideological leaning and political party leanings. These are used as response variables in the regression models.

The data also includes survey weights.

def clean_data(raw_data):
    ''' Cleans data, handles missing values, and encodes dummies.
    
    Args:
    raw_data: Pandas DataFrame. The raw data imported from csv copy of survey results.
    
    Returns:
    fs_df: Pandas DataFrame. Contains formatted feature variables, excluding FS_Index.
    y: Pandas DataFrame. Contains response variable dummies.
    wt: Pandas Series. Contains survey weights.
    FS_Index: Pandas Series. Contains Stanton Free Speech Index variable.
    
    '''
    
    fs_df = raw_data[['ageban', 'genderban', 'relban', 'soc_classrec', 'arearec',
                      'Race_Black', 'Race_Hispanic', 'Race_Asian', 'Race_Other',
                      'Region_East', 'Region_MidWest', 'Region_South',
                      'Institution_Public',
                      'FSI_Q4', 'FSI_Q4A', 'FSI_Q14A', 'FSI_Q14B', 'FSI_Q34A', 
                      'FSI_Q34B', 'FSI_Q34D', 'FSI_Q34E', 'FSI_Q34F', 'FSI_Q35A', 
                      'FSI_Q35C', 'FSI_Q35D', 'FSI_Q40B', 'FSI_Q41', 'FSI_Q43',
                      'PARTYL', 'ideolrec', 'finalwt', 'FS_Index', 'D10']].copy()

    # Drop if missing response variable(s)
    fs_df = fs_df.dropna(subset=['PARTYL', 'ideolrec', 'D10'])

    # Separate response, feature, and survey weight variables
    y = fs_df[['PARTYL', 'ideolrec', 'D10']].copy()
    wt = 1 / fs_df['finalwt'].copy()
    FS_Index = fs_df['FS_Index'].copy().astype('float')
    fs_df = fs_df.drop(columns=['PARTYL', 'ideolrec', 'finalwt', 'FS_Index', 'D10'])
    
    # Combine Q4 and Q4A into one variable, per the data dictionary guideline
    fs_df['FSI_Q4'].replace(np.nan, fs_df['FSI_Q4A'], inplace=True)
    fs_df = fs_df.drop(columns=['FSI_Q4A'])
    fs_df['FSI_Q4'].replace(['An open learning environment', 'A positive learning environment', 
                             'Allow all types of speech', 'Prohibit offensive speech'], 
                            ['1', '0', '1', '0'], inplace=True)
    fs_df['FSI_Q4'] = pd.to_numeric(fs_df['FSI_Q4'])

    # I am grouping those with no religion with those who are agnostic
    fs_df['relban'].replace('No opinion', 'No religion', inplace=True)

    # Replace "No opinon" with np.nan for variables that are not subjective
    fs_df['soc_classrec'].replace('No opinion', np.nan, inplace=True)
    fs_df['arearec'].replace('No opinion', np.nan, inplace=True)

    # Replace string labels with integers in FSI variables to make sure 1 = free speech and 0 = protective policies
    # This will facilitate mean imputation
    cat_cols = fs_df.select_dtypes(['category']).columns
    fs_df[cat_cols] = fs_df[cat_cols].apply(lambda x: x.cat.codes)
    fs_df['FSI_Q34A'].replace([0, 1, 2, -1], [0, 0.5, 1, np.nan], inplace=True)
    fs_df['FSI_Q34B'].replace([0, 1, 2, -1], [0, 0.5, 1, np.nan], inplace=True)
    fs_df['FSI_Q34D'].replace([0, 1, 2, -1], [0, 0.5, 1, np.nan], inplace=True)
    fs_df['FSI_Q34E'].replace([0, 1, 2, -1], [0, 0.5, 1, np.nan], inplace=True)
    fs_df['FSI_Q34F'].replace([0, 1, 2, -1], [0, 0.5, 1, np.nan], inplace=True)
    fs_df['FSI_Q40B'].replace([0, 1, 2, 3, -1], [0, 0.33, 0.66, 1, np.nan], inplace=True)
    fs_df.replace(-1, np.nan, inplace=True)
    fs_df['FSI_Q43'] = fs_df['FSI_Q43'].copy() * -1 + 1 # reversing the 0 and 1
    
    # Impute missing values of categorical variables with mode
    fs_df[['soc_classrec', 'arearec']] = SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent').fit_transform(fs_df[['soc_classrec', 'arearec']])

    # Impute missing values of ordinal variables with mean
    fs_df = pd.DataFrame(SimpleImputer().fit_transform(fs_df), columns=fs_df.columns)
    
    # Get dummies
    fs_df = pd.get_dummies(fs_df, columns=['genderban', 'relban', 'soc_classrec', 'arearec'], drop_first=True)
    
    # Do cool things with response variables
    y = pd.get_dummies(y, drop_first=False)
    y = y.drop(columns=['PARTYL_Libertarian', 'PARTYL_No opinion', 'ideolrec_DK', 'ideolrec_REF', 'D10_No opinion'])

    return fs_df, y, wt, FS_Index

The Stanton Foundation Free Speech Index (FSI) value for each student is the sum of their values for the variables prefixed by 'FSI_'.

The FSI appears to be approximately normally distributed among students as a whole, but distributions differ when conditioned on ideology or political party affiliation.

Question 1: Can we identify latent variables associated with general positions on free speech?¶

Reducing Dimensionality with PCA¶

PCA is a (relatively) simple approach to dimensionality reduction and latent variable discovery. You can read more about latent variables on Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latent_variable.

First I create the principal components. I take a look at their explanatory power and their sample distributions. I then take a shot at interpreting the most important principal components as latent variables, which is an inherently subjective practice.

Non-math PCA explanation: PCA takes an original set of variables and produces a set of new variables we can order from "best" to "worst", where "best" is defined as that which explains the most variation in the original set of variables. When a sample size is sufficiently large, it becomes accurate to say PCA produces the best new variables that can be produced using any similar (i.e. linear) method.

The new variables can sometimes be interpreted to represent real, underlying concepts (latent variables). A classic exmaple is the use of PCA to provide support for the concept of General IQ.

PCA can also be used to reduce the number of variables used in an analysis by using only the best of the new variables. This works because the best of the new variables will

Math PCA explanation: Principal Components Analysis(PCA) uses a singular value decomposition to decompose X into UDV. The matrix U is an orthonormal matrix with columns Xv multiplied by the inverse of D, D is a diagonal matrix with the eigenvalues of X'X along the diagonals, and V is a matrix of eigenvectors for X'X that correspond to the eigenvalues in D and the columns of U. Pragmatically and by convention, the matrices are ordered such that the elements of D are arranged from largest to smallest in absolute value. Note that UD=Xv. PCA is a linear transformation producing a matrix W which minimizes the objective function ||X'X-WW'||^2. PCA provides the rank-optimal matrix W such that we can reduce the rank of W and X by some number k and maintain matrices that minimize ||X'X-WW'||^2 where each of X'X and WW' now have rank=rank(X)-k.

The diagonal elements of D are scalars representing the portion of the variance of X explained by the vector UD=Xv. The vectors v, the columns of V, are directions in the original vector space corresponding to the columns of X (as implied by the equivalence of UD and Xv). We can use V to transform the vectors of UD back to the original feature space.

Conceptually, we can view PCA as a rotation of the original feature space axes to produce a new set of axes that point in the directions which maximize the variance explained by each axis. We are effectively creating each new axis one at a time so that each axis maximizes the variance it explains while maintaining orthogonality with all already-created transformed axes.

Discussion: The Curse of Dimensionality¶

Let's take a moment to discuss the curse of dimensionality. As the number of dimensions increases, the density of the sample in the K-dimensional space decreases. With too many features relative to our sample size, a growing proportion of points become distribution outliers. It is possible for a majority of points to be outliers.

The metric I will use to assess the density of the sample in the transformed feature space is based on a hypothetical situation. Suppose our data were uniformly distributed within a unit hypersphere centered at the origin. The sampling density is then proportional to N^(1/p). In other words, to get the same sampling density with 10 inputs as you would have with only 1 input you will need N^10 observations.

This metric is conservative because variables are rarely uniformly distributed. Rather, we very often can often expect substantially more concentrated (i.e. narrower, lower variance) distributions. This is what we observe in our transformed dataset. The distributions of the six "best" (most variance explained) principal components are displayed below.

Discussion: How many dimensions?¶

There is a tradeoff between dimensionality reduction and explanatory power. The more tranformed features used, the more information we retain. However, as we increase dimensions in the transformed feature space we quickly run into the "curse of dimensionality", reducing the likelihood we can find coherent and meaningful clusters.

Principal components as latent variables¶

We can interpet principal components as latent variables if underlying latent variables exist. Such interpretations are somewhat subjective. We risk assuming latent variables exist even when they do not exist in the population.

In [17]:
# takes a list of feature labels from a dataframe fitted to PCA, the fitted PCA object, and eigenvector index k
# returns list of label-weight tuples sorted by weight in descending order
# weights are singular value k * kth eigenvector
# i.e. returns weight of each feature associated with principal direction k
# assumes feature labels are in the same order as the data columns fitted to PCA
def map_pca_weights(labels, pca, k):
    sv = pca.singular_values_[k]
    v = pca.components_[k]
    fw_pairs = zip(labels, v*sv)
    sorted_fw_pairs = sorted(fw_pairs, key=lambda x: abs(x[1]), reverse=True)
    return list(sorted_fw_pairs)

def plot_pca_weight_map(fw_pairs, pc_num):
    # plot feature-weight pairs
    features, weights = zip(*fw_pairs)
    plt.barh(range(len(features)), weights, height=0.7, zorder=2)
    plt.yticks(range(len(features)), features)
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='-.', zorder=1)
    plt.axvline(color='black')
    plt.title(f'Weight of Principal Component {pc_num} in Direction of Each Feature')
    plt.ylabel('Feature', rotation='horizontal', labelpad=30)
    plt.xlabel('Weight')
    plt.show()

Discussion: Latent variables¶

We can arguably label the first principal component "Political Correctness", which accounts for about 23% of the variance in students' beliefs about free speech.

The "Political Correctness" factor measures preference for protective inclusiveness in lieu of free expression. It is a measure of the extent to which students believe the value of promoting an inclusive society is more important than freedom of express. Students high in this metric favor "instituting speech codes" that could restrict "offensive or biased speech" on campus, removing first amendment protection of hate speech, and "disinviting [sic] speakers because some students are opposed to the invitation".

I found additional evidence for a quality we might label "free speech moderation", the second principal component. Students high in this metric support free speech in general-they believe hate speech should be legally protected, for example-but also want some regulation of speech on campus.

The statistical process also uncovered a third variable I'd like to call "free speech extremism", the third principal component. It measures the extent to which a student expresses blanket support for free speech, including the use of speech to counter unwanted speakers-e.g. by protesting, shouting.

2. Can students be clustered by their positions on free speech?¶

Here I implement clustering methods and juxtapose their performance. I do so first using subsets of the latent variables constructed using PCA, and then instead using the original FSI variables.

I test multiple clustering strategies:

  • K-Means
  • Guassian Mixture Model
  • Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise (DBSCAN)
  • Agglomerative

Note that this version of the notebook only retains code for K-Means. This makes the notebook more readable. I kept K-Means because it performed at least as well as the other models, is conceptually simple, and is computationally efficient. You can find results for the other methods in an earlier Git commit.

I use three internal metrics for each model: the objective function, the Silhouette score, and the Calinski-Harabaz score. Both of the latter metrics increase as cluster coherence improves. I print and graph the metric valuations for each hyperparameter combination. I did not use GridSearchCV because it isn't friendly with the Silhouette score as a custom scorer.

The Silhouette score is a ratio measure of differences in distances between points within clusters and points in nearby clusters. For more information on the Silhouette score, see here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/clustering.html#silhouette-coefficient

The Calinksi-Harabaz score is the ratio of the between-cluster variance to the within-cluster variance in the sample. For more information on the Calinski-Harabaz score, see here: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/clustering.html#calinski-harabaz-index

After

K-Means clustering using latent variable subsets¶

In [21]:
# Run algorithm, varying hyperparameters

kmeans_metrics = []

num_means = 20
num_components = 10

for t in range(1, num_components+1):
    
    # Get dataframe with best k components for analysis
    df_T = df_pc.iloc[:,0:t]
    
    # instantiate collections
    objective = []
    silhouette = []
    calinski_harabaz = []
    
    # estimate clustering model for t components
    for k in range(2, num_means+1):

        kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=23953)
        predictions = kmeans.fit_predict(df_T, sample_weight=wt)

        o = -kmeans.score(df_T, sample_weight=wt) / df_T.shape[0]
        objective.append(o)

        s = silhouette_score(df_T, predictions)
        silhouette.append(s)

        ch = calinski_harabaz_score(df_T, predictions)
        calinski_harabaz.append(ch)
        
    # print and save results for iteration with t components
    print(f'Completed iteration with {t} dimensions')
    kmeans_metrics.append({'objective': objective, 'silhouette': silhouette, 'ch': calinski_harabaz})

Clustering Discussion: No clear clusters?¶

It seems there are no obvious ways to form clusters based on the free speech variables. The internal validation metrics used indicate we can use a two cluster solution without practical loss of coherence. The solution would use one or two principal components. The metrics also indicate we may as well use K-Means, rather than "fancier" algorithms, to produce our clusters--especially since the fancier algorithms preclude the use of survey sampling weights.

In [24]:

K-Means clustering with original set of FS variables¶

num_means = 10
df_T = fs_vars

# instantiate collections
kmeans_metrics = []
objective = []
silhouette = []
calinski_harabaz = []

# estimate clustering model for t components
for k in range(2, num_means+1):

    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=23953)
    predictions = kmeans.fit_predict(df_T, sample_weight=wt)

    o = -kmeans.score(df_T, sample_weight=wt) / df_T.shape[0]
    objective.append(o)

    s = silhouette_score(df_T, predictions)
    silhouette.append(s)

    ch = calinski_harabaz_score(df_T, predictions)
    calinski_harabaz.append(ch)

    # print and save results for iteration with t components
    print(f'Completed iteration with {k} means')
kmeans_metrics.append({'objective': objective, 'silhouette': silhouette, 'ch': calinski_harabaz})

3. What are the relationships between viable clusters or latent variables and students' political affiliations?¶

I assess relationships between latent variables and political affiliations using OLS regression. I use OLS because most of the variables are dummy variables or approximately normally distributed. The exception is "ageban", which has five discrete, ordered age values. The model will theoretically fit well for our purposes. Linear probability model parameters tend to be very similar to marginal effects produced by nonlinear models such as logit and probit.

I did not use more "advanced" prediction models because I am not seeking to predict out-of-sample values. I am exploring variable relationships. I want interpretable parameters from a reasonable model. OLS is perfeclty suited for the job at hand.

We might be concerned that I didn't bootstrap the standard errors to account for pre-processing. This is something we may want to keep in mind when looking at p-values. Bootstrapped standard errors would be more accurate and could be slightly larger than those which ignore variability from pre-processing.

Discussion: relationships between free speech and political affiliations¶

There is a statistically significant relationship between the Stanton Free Speech Index and political ideology/party affiliation among college students that persists after accounting for factors socioeconomic status, college region, college sector, gender, religion and race. Conservative students tend to have more support for free speech than do moderate students, while liberal students tend to have stronger preference for protective speech policies than moderate students. And while Democrat students are less likely than Independent students to support free speech, Republic students support free speech to about the same degree as Independent students. Despite those differences, the distributions of free speech index scores retain substantial overlap when stratified by ideology or political party leanings.

Interestingly, the trait "political correctness" is a better predictor of a college student's political ideology than socioeconomic status, religion, age, gender, race, college sector, or college geographical region.
